\par \pard\plain\f2\fs24\b 3.0\tab CUSTOM GRAPHICS LEVELS
\par \plain\f2\fs20\b 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 Worms Armageddon\plain\f2\fs20  features an option to load an accepted standard graphics file into the Terrain Editor in order to make a completely new level to play on. Whilst the actual technical procedures of this process are fairly complex, we have endeavoured to make this as easy to achieve as is possible for the end user.
\par 
\par There are a number of rules to follow and a number of things you can keep in mind in order to ensure that your levels look and play as good as they can be.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Accepted Image Formats
\par \plain\f2\fs20 The editor will import the most commonly accepted image formats, including Bitmap, JPEG and Targa standard. These files must be of a compliant \plain\f2\fs20\b .bmp\plain\f2\fs20  \plain\f2\fs20\b .jpg\plain\f2\fs20  or \plain\f2\fs20\b .tga \plain\f2\fs20 file extension type and other than that there are no requirements to load your images in a special format.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Specified Image Size
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Whilst the pixel size of the terrain is \plain\f2\fs20\b 1920x696 \plain\f2\fs20 the size and proportion of your imported graphic is not important. The editor will shrink the file if it is larger, or offer to expand or centre it if it is smaller.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Transparency/Background Colour
\par \plain\f2\fs20 The \plain\f2\fs20\b most important\plain\f2\fs20  thing to note is that any pixel that is coloured \plain\f2\fs20\b black\plain\f2\fs20  (i.e. RGB 0,0,0) will be treated as transparent. It is these areas that will act as the background, where worms are placed and can move. 
\par 
\par You can edit the image you wish to import in any of the popular image processing applications, colouring \plain\f2\fs20\b black\plain\f2\fs20  any areas that you wish to appear as transparent/background in the game. This way, you can clear sections, add tunnels and more besides. It is important to note that the game will check levels and make it's own holes if a level does not have enough free background space to start the game.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Minor inconveniences...
\par \plain\f2\fs20 It is \plain\f2\fs20\cf2 not\plain\f2\fs20  possible to use the terrain editor painting functions with full colour levels. The levels are processed in a different format. If you wish to edit the import graphics, then use Microsoft Paint\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 \'99\plain\f2\fs20 , Adobe's Photoshop\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 \'99\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b  \plain\f2\fs20 or a similar application.
\par 
\par It is \plain\f2\fs20\cf2 not\plain\f2\fs20  possible to play on full colour custom levels in Internet games unless every player has the same level, since the time taken to transmit the file to each player would be too prohibitive.
\par 
\par Some clipping of the level may occur if the height is too great (i.e. more than 696 pixels).\tab 
\par \plain\f2\fs14 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Unfortunately it is \plain\f2\fs20\cf2 not\plain\f2\fs20  possible to edit the starting water level with a full colour custom level. This is due to the fact that changing the water level would mean re-processing of the image every time, which takes time. Should you wish your level to start nearer the water, we suggest that you edit the image directly in an image processing application and move the graphics towards the bottom of the screen. 
\par 
\par \pard\li720\fi-720\plain\lang1033\f2\fs20\cf1\b\i 3.1\tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\b\i Using the graphics
\par \pard\plain\f2\fs20 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Import file destination folder requirements and implementation\plain\f2\fs20 
\par Simply copy your image to the \plain\f2\fs20\cf4\b USER/IMPORT\plain\f2\fs20  folder in the \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 Worms Armageddon \plain\f2\fs20 game directory (an optional shortcut can made to the desktop for this purpose). 
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\b\i 3.2\tab Options
\par \plain\f2\fs20\b 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Stretch or centre the image
\par \plain\f2\fs20 If you load an image which is smaller than the terrain size (i.e. less than 1920x696 in proportion) you will be asked if you would like to;
\par 
\par \pard\li360\fi-360\tx360{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'b7}}\plain\f2\fs20 {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Stretch the image\tab - in this case the image will be stretched to fill the entire terrain area. 
\par {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Centre the image\tab - in this case the image will be placed in the middle of the terrain.
\par \pard\plain\f2\fs20 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\b 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\b\i 3.3\tab Hints and tips to make the most out of Custom Levels\plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Colour Usage
\par \plain\f2\fs20 It is important to realise that Worms Armageddon uses a fixed colour palette during the game. This is for a number of technical reasons, not least the performance of the game's sprite engine. 
\par 
\par Since it is a fixed palette, all the colours for everything on screen must be included in this palette, including colours that must not change (i.e. Worm colours, weapon colours and effects, water, explosions etc.) 
\par 
\par The number of colours than can change during a level is fairly limited and the editor will have to take all this into consideration when it colour-processes any image that you import. The result being that the more colour information the picture is comprised of, the lower quality the results will be. Colour digitised images are most likely to be grainy and washed out in appearance.
\par 
\par To get an idea of what the results may be \plain\f2\fs20\i before\plain\f2\fs20  you import the image, you could use a colour reduction tool in a graphics application to reduce the image to 64 or 128 colours (a 6 or 7bit colour palette).
\par 
\par For these reasons, it's quite important to 'clean up' your image before importing it into the editor, removing large areas of background and colour that would otherwise consume areas of the colour palette.
\par 
\par The best way to build levels is to draw onto, begin from or render to a black background.
\par \plain\f2\fs20\b\i 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Image Size
\par \plain\f2\fs20 The smaller an image is, the greater loss of detail will be when stretched up to fill the level. If you would like to make the best use of the available area, then create a new image which is 1920x696 pixels in size and save your import levels with that size.
\par 
\par The editor currently doesn't handle very small images well.
\par \plain\f2\fs20\b\i 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Background Considerations
\par \plain\f2\fs20 If you intend importing digitised images, you will have to consider that a lot of images will result in a 'solid' level since there is not much background. The game will create holes to play in, but the level will not play particularly well. It's best to clear some area for background prior to importing. See the notes on colour usage.\plain\f2\fs20\b\i 
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Getting your created images to other people
\par \plain\f2\fs20 The world wide web is by far the best method, many WORMS sites exist and it's also a tremendous source for multitudes of images you could use as imported levels - search away!
\par 
\par Check out \plain\f2\fs20\b http://worms.team17.com\plain\f2\fs20  for files and links to other sites that carry files.\plain\f2\fs20\b\i 
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 
\par \pard\ri-37\plain\f2\fs24\b 4.0\tab IN-GAME MODIFICATONS\plain\f2\fs24 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Worm Placement
\par \plain\f2\fs20 When the game cannot place Worms in the current landscape, it will endeavour to place Worms either by placing a small girder in open space or by creating a hole in which to put the Worm. This process is automatic and is more likely to be used when encountering user-defined landscapes with little or too much land area. The result of this can be seen within the terrain editor.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Manual Worm Placement
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 An option has been added which provides the opportunity for players to teleport their Worms into the playfield at the beginning of a round. The game continues when all Worms are placed. This feature is in the game options and is meant for pure strategists.\plain\f2\fs20 
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Weapons Arriving As Reinforcements
\par \plain\f2\fs20 When weapons are subject to delays (configurable in the weapon options) they will appear shaded in the Weapon selection box and the text of the weapon will be red. You are notified by the message system if Reinforcements arrive.
\par \plain\f2\fs20\b 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Border In Cavern Levels
\par \plain\f2\fs20 A border will now be placed at the top of Cavern levels \endash  this is to ensure that Worms can't 'cheat'. When playing in such a level, the scrolling is locked.  
\par 
\par An optional full border (completely encompassing the terrain) is available within the terrain menu and, in effect, means that it is impossible for worms to drown.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i The Viking Axe
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 U\plain\f2\fs20 sing the Axe with slice half of the energy off any Worm touched.It will only kill a Worm which has 1 unit of energy, but can be devastating against a Worm with a lot of energy!
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Hostage Worms
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 Note that some missions require the player to guard special Worms. These Worms are recognised by the special crown they wear. They cannot be moved.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Lingering Fire\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\i 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 A special feature has been added to the Petrol Bomb weapon in that this weapon produces fire which burns for a number of turns, providing you with the means to set up a burning section of the terrain as traps.
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i 
\par Default Schemes
\par \plain\f2\fs20 We have provided a variety of different game schemes for you to experiment with. 
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Enable Super Weapons
\par \plain\f2\fs20 You can now turn the more powerful 'super weapons' on or off. They're still quite rare, but more conservative players may prefer a more balanced game without them.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Caves in the Terrain Editor
\par \plain\f2\fs20 There is a rule which applies to landscapes which affects whether they will play as Islands or Caverns (Caverns have a bordered roof and the game will not scroll outside the playfield area).
\par 
\par If the top line or sides of the terrain are touched, the level will automatically play as a Cavern. This is indicated by a striped border appearing about the level and is further reinforced by the help text.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f2\fs20\b\i 
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs24\b 5.0\tab SPEECH BANKS
\par \plain\f2\fs20\b 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Worms Armageddon features the ability to create or modify any of the existing Speech Banks using ordinary wave format (\plain\f2\fs20\b .wav\plain\f2\fs20 ) sound samples. It is also compatible with the hundreds of the existing Worms2\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 \'99\plain\f2\fs20  soundbanks that are available on the Internet.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\b\i 5.1\tab Using the Sound Bank Editor
\par \plain\f2\fs20\b 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 The Sound Bank Editor is a separate utility from the main Worms Armageddon program and runs in the Windows desktop environment for total ease of use when transferring sound files. 
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Scheme
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Select a sound-bank file from the list. This list is obtained by looking in the \plain\f2\fs20\cf4 USER\\SPEECH\plain\f2\fs20  folder within your Worms Armageddon directory. 
\par 
\par To add soundbanks, simply place them within this folder. The Sound Bank Editor and the game will then automatically detect a given soundbank and make it available for use.
\par 
\par By default, the English set has been placed in the folder to enable you to start modifying a new set immediately.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Save As...\plain\f2\fs20\i 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 When you have finished modifying your sound-set, you can save it with a new name. This will be created in the \plain\f2\fs20\cf4 USER\\SPEECH\plain\f2\fs20\b  \plain\f2\fs20 folder and will be detected by the game. You can copy this folder to friends or upload onto the Internet.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Delete
\par \plain\f2\fs20 You can opt to delete the selected set if you wish.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Sample List
\par \plain\f2\fs20 A list of the samples that are used in the game are shown in the main screen. Also displayed is the size of the sample, it's important to realise that larger soundsets take much more memory to run (affecting the performance of the game, considering up to six different sound-banks can be loaded at any one time).
\par 
\par You can double-click on a name to hear the current sample held for that effect.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Play
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Play the currently highlighted sample.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Stop
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Stop playing the current sample.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Set
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Brings up a file selection box, you can look for other samples to replace the current one. You may also preview (hear) the samples you are looking at whilst you do this.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Restore
\par \plain\f2\fs20 If you make any changes, you can restore the sample set to default.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\i Game loading speed\plain\f2\fs20\cf1\b\i 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Since all the default speech banks (some 50+) are now held on the game CD, you can increase loading performance by having these speech banks present on your Hard Drive (in \plain\f2\fs20\cf4 USER\\SPEECH\plain\f2\fs20 ). However, please note that each set takes up 1-4mb in size. All the supplied sound sets would take up in excess of 120Mb of hard drive space!
\par 
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs24\b 6.0\tab CUSTOM BANNERS
\par \plain\f2\fs20\b 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 Worms Armageddon features the ability to modify a team banner or flag. Simply change/modify one of the flags in \plain\f2\fs20\cf4 USER\\FLAGS \plain\f2\fs20 in the Worms Armageddon directory, save it and you can access it in the game (from within team options). You may edit and create new flags by using Microsoft Paint(R).
\par 
\par This facility is really useful for players who enjoy Allied (CLAN) games on network events.
\par 
\par A number of user designed flags have been included with the game, our thanks to everyone who submitted them.
\par 
